<div id="3.1.1.1">		



<span class="section_title">Latest Technology for the Connected Home Showcased at 2003 International CES</span>

<br><br>		
<strong><i>New York, New York&nbsp;-&nbsp;11/6/2002</i></strong>
<br><br>
The latest products and technology for the $15 billion connected home industry will be showcased at the 2003 International CES, the world's largest consumer technology tradeshow, January 9-12, 2003 in Las Vegas, Nev.  <p>

"As the country continues to experience the boom in new home sales and existing home improvement, the need for advance connected home technology is facing strong consumer demand," said Karen Chupka, vice president of events and conferences for the Consumer Electronics Association (CEA), the producer of CES.  "The International CES is the place to see the latest and greatest in home networking and home entertainment technology and learn about the latest trends helping fuel this technological revolution within the home."<p>
CEA will showcase the technological advances for the home in a vibrant demo display on the show floor.  The CEA "Tech Home Demo," located in the lower level of the South Hall, will display home networking technology for the kitchen, bedroom, utility room and recreation room of today's advanced homes.  Also included in the home networking technology pavilions is the Home Plug Powerline Alliance Pavilion.<p>

Several CES conference sessions will focus on the home networking industry.  Some sessions include:
* The Reality Check Road Show: Developments in the Networked Home
* Follow the Money: The Digital Entertainment Value Chain
* The Networked Home & the Connected Consumer - How Technology Transforms the Future
* Home Secure Home
* Better Living Through Technology<p>
In addition, home networking technology will be discussed in several CES SuperSessions as well.  During CNET Networks Reveals the Next Big Things in CE-Now, Next Year and Beyond," ZDNet AnchorDesk Executive Editor David Coursey and CNET Computer Shopper Editor-in-Chief Janice Chen showcase their discovery of new technologies that will become the category killers of the future.  The "Tomorrow's Technologies SuperSession" features John Rennie, editor-in-chief of Scientific American, moderating this session that takes a look into the future of the consumer technology industry. <p> 

The CEDIA installer training program will offer multiple sessions in the areas of home theater, home networking, essential technologies, whole-house systems and business management for custom designers and installers.  CEDIA will deliver two of its professional certification prep courses; the installer level I and installer level II seminars offer the opportunity to take the professional certification exam for both installer levels.<p>

CES is North America's largest technology tradeshow by a factor of two.  Recently, Tradeshow Week announced it was the largest show of any kind.  The 2003 International CES will showcase the latest innovations from 2,000 international exhibitors in wireless communications, gaming, digital video, high-end or "extreme" audio, accessories, CE fashion, consumer technology networking, broadband, mobile electronics, content media, new business technology, delivery systems and the Internet.  
Online registration is available at www.CESweb.org, the interactive source for CES information.<p>

<b>About CEA:<p></b><br>
The Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) represents more than 1000 corporate members involved in the design, development, manufacturing and distribution of audio, video, mobile electronics, wireless and landline communications, information technology, multimedia and accessory products, as well as related services that are sold through consumer channels.  Combined, CEA's members account for more than $80 billion in annual sales.  CEA's resources are available online at www.CE.org, the definitive source for information about the consumer electronics industry.<p>
CEA also sponsors and manages the International CES - Defining Technology's Future.  All profits from CES are reinvested into industry services, including technical training and education, industry promotion, engineering standards development, market research and legislative advocacy.


